if this is a real use case, I'd test the copy on 
```
settings = {
  'distributed_tracing': True,
  'foo': ['bar', 'baz'],
}

Getting this every time is going to be super slow. We should just get the id in this step. You can just grab that from the `summary_id` property of `alert`. Since we just need the integer id, we could probably simplify this to something like (untested):

```js
alertSummary.downstreamSummaryIds = _.uniq(_.flatten(_.map(alertSummary.alerts, function(alert) {
  if (alert.status === phAlertStatusMap.DOWNSTREAM.id && alert.summary_id !== alertSummary.id ) {
      return alert.summary_id;
  } else {
      return [];
  }
})));
```

Check out the lodash documentation if you're unclear on what any of that means. :)

No problem, I just wanted to document it so that other 1.7 users know that [0.7.2 fails](https://github.com/cobrateam/splinter/blob/0.7.2/splinter/driver/djangoclient.py#L154). I don't think it's necesary to change anything as it seems that it's already [fixed in master](https://github.com/cobrateam/splinter/blob/master/splinter/driver/djangoclient.py#L172):

    return self._response.content.decode(self._response._charset or 'utf-8')

This should be working in 0.7.3. :smile:

C++ way would be to express the algorithm at a higher level like this:
`std::find_if(entry->task_queue->begin(), entry->task_queue->end(), [&](TaskQueueEntry &v)
{
	return task_counter > TaskSpec_actor_counter(v);
})`

@jakubwasikowski we're not strict about it, but I think a convention which we follow is to use 79 columns - both for code and docstrings, unless there is a reason not to do so. 

Regarding "reason": introducing a local variable to make an expression fit to a limit is fine; splitting a string constant with a long URL just to fit it to 79 columns is not a good idea.

It may also depend on a project: it is fine to use 120 columns limit if you notice that the project doesn't respect 79 columns limit often; if code is mostly fit into 79 columns, it is better to go with that limit, so that the code is consistent - unless there is a strong reason to diverge.

